isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.29) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.09. The models intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 11.50 (S.E. = 1.29, p < .001, 95% CI [8.97, 14.03]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -1.50, S.E. = 2.24, p = 0.503, 95% CI [-5.89, 2.89]; Std. beta = -0.67, 95% CI [-2.63, 1.29])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -1.61, S.E. = 1.77, p = 0.362, 95% CI [-5.08, 1.85]; Std. beta = -0.72, 95% CI [-2.26, 0.83])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.30, S.E. = 2.04, p = 0.884, 95% CI [-3.69, 4.29]; Std. beta = 0.13, 95% CI [-1.65, 1.91])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 1.61, S.E. = 2.88, p = 0.576, 95% CI [-4.04, 7.26]; Std. beta = 0.72, 95% CI [-1.80, 3.24])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.70, S.E. = 3.06, p = 0.818, 95% CI [-5.28, 6.69]; Std. beta = 0.31, 95% CI [-2.36, 2.98])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
